                "href": "/profile/Tyler-Borchers"
            },
            "answer_text": "Because the bickering is important! The candidates' personal interactions are just as insightful as their political substance. If a candidate is too assertive, the audience might consider him or her overly aggressive. If a candidate is too quiet, he or she might be thought of as overly submissive. It is critical that a voting public be exposed to these rhetorical characteristics of candidates. Being able to negotiate a tense conversation and communicate convincingly among dissimilar peers are essential traits for any president to have. What you want are two candidates who don't bicker, not two candidates whose tendencies to bicker are hidden from public knowledge. ",
